-- South Africa Shares: Anglo, Billiton, FirstRand, First Uranium
-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 2012-06-07T15:46:56Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-07/south-africa-shares-acucap-first-uranium-transaction-capital.html
The  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index (JALSH) 
rose to the highest in almost four weeks, advancing 0.9 percent
to 33,904.86 by the close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active equities in the
market today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  , the diversified miner that
makes up more than 7 percent of the index, gained for a fifth
day, climbing 1.6 percent to 275.23 rand. Commodities rallied
after  China  cut  interest rates  for the first time since 2008 to
combat a deepening economic slowdown.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BIL)  , the world’s biggest resources
company, jumped 2.7 percent to 236.34 rand.  FirstRand Ltd. (FSR)  ,  South Africa ’s second-biggest
banking group, advanced 2.7 percent to 26.95 rand, the highest
since at least 1990 when Bloomberg started compiling data on the
stock. South African banks rallied after China’s rate cut,
fueling speculation more central banks will take steps to boost
economic growth.  First Uranium Corp. (FUM)  , a uranium and gold producer,
gained the most on record as it surged 82 percent to 1.20 rand.
The company increased its proposed distribution to shareholders
once it sells assets to AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. and Gold One
International Ltd.  Peregrine Holdings Ltd. (PGR)  , a money manager and
stockbroker, rose to the highest in almost five months, climbing
9 percent to 12 rand. The company doubled its final dividend for
the year through March and declared a special distribution of
shares in Consolidated Infrastructure Group Ltd.  To contact the reporter on this story:
